Xi Jing, artistic director of Hyundai Motorstudio Beijing, introduces the jury panel for the Hyundai Blue Prize at a media briefing in Beijing on Thursday. Photo: Courtesy of Ji HengSix groups of nominees competed to become the final two winners of the Hyundai Blue Prize 2019 on Thursday in Beijing. The finalists for the competition, themed Social Intelligence,were chosen after a 10-month selection process.  According to Xu Jing, artistic director of Hyundai Motorstudio Beijing, the final winners will be decided by a six-member international jury of artists, art critics and curators, including Gao Minglu, a professor at Pittsburg Univeserity; Stephanie Rosenthal, director of Berlin's Martin-Gropius-Bau Museum and Qiu Zhijie from China's Central Academy of Fine Arts, as well 18 votes from the media. The six nominee teams presented their ideas and thinking toward the future of global social development and people-to-people exchanges. Since 2017, the Hyundai Blue Prize has aimed to provide an international stage and platform to young Chinese curators, who are willing to use scientific and technological means to guide people in thinking about the present and future of social development. Past winners include Long Xingru for her AI-themed exhibition and Li Jia for her new media work titled The Precariousness, which explores social changes in a rapidly developing society. The final results for this year's competition will release soon. 
